solution.p:
Let (x,y) be a representative point on the curve in xy plane that has potential equal to 1.0\text{ V}. For brevity, will suppress units in our calculations. Let V_1(x,y) and V_2(x,y) be the potentials there by the two charges. Therefore, by using superposition we get

	V_1(x,y) + V_2(x,y) = 1.

Now, we can see what these individual potentials are.

	V_1(x,y) \amp = \frac{q_1}{4\pi\epsilon_0} \frac{1}{\sqrt{ (x-0.5)^2 + y^2 }} 
	  \amp = 9\times 10^9 \times 6\times 10^{-9} \frac{1}{\sqrt{ (x-0.5)^2 + y^2 }} 
	  \amp =  \frac{54}{\sqrt{ (x-0.5)^2 + y^2 }} 
	V_2(x,y) \amp = \frac{q_2}{4\pi\epsilon_0} \frac{1}{\sqrt{ (x+0.5)^2 + y^2 }} 	
	  \amp =  -\frac{54}{\sqrt{ (x+0.5)^2 + y^2 }} 					

Therefore, the loci are values of x,y that satisfy the following equation.

	\frac{54}{\sqrt{ (x-0.5)^2 + y^2 }} -\frac{54}{\sqrt{ (x+0.5)^2 + y^2 }} = 1.

statement.p:
You can use the following result from . Let r be the distance from center of this cloud to the field point. Then, we have worked out the potentials at outisde and inside points to be

	\phi(r) = 
	\begin{cases}
		\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\,\frac{q}{r}, \amp r \gt R\\
		\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0} \frac{q}{R} \left( \frac{3}{2} - \frac{1}{2}\; \frac{r^2}{R^2} \right), \amp r\le R.
	\end{cases}
